 but it's definitely hearable, and I hope you get something useful out of it.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:22.000
 All right, here's Ray Peat on WGDR Radio circa 2000-2001.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
 I wanted to talk about diet again today.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
 I think that's something that everybody can relate to.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:38.000
 And one of the things I've been confused about is,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:44.000
 we say that sugar is important, and I was wondering what kind of sugar is important.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:52.000
 And I was also wondering, you've also mentioned about the Western diet and its relationship to diabetes,

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
 and I was wondering how that works.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:09.000
 Oh, there are several things that are well known about the diet that should be important factors in causing it,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:19.000
 but the studies in humans aren't entirely clear on how the diet works.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:30.000
 The animal studies are pretty clear, and then there's a little bit of epidemiological information on humans.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:45.000
 For example, when Israel was developing, the European Jews had the regular European high incidence of diabetes,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:58.000
 but the immigrants who had been living in Africa or other parts of the world had very low diabetes rates.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.000
 And after they had been living 10 or 20 years in Israel and starting to eat the European diet,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
 they came right up to the European high diabetes rate.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:23.000
 And so it shows that the old idea that you inherit diabetes is just completely unfounded.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:33.000
 It might rarely happen, but the basic problem is strictly a dietary problem that develops in a person's lifetime.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:46.000
 And the Argentine physiologist who got the Nobel Prize about 50 years ago, Bernardo Husai,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:58.000
 he in the '40s was experimenting with different diets and mice and what things would contribute to diabetes.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:11.000
 And he showed that coconut oil was the most protective food against developing diabetes caused by poisoning, for example,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:31.000
 and that sugar was the next most protective dietary factor, and that foods high in unsaturated fats as opposed to coconut oil didn't offer protection.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:41.000
 And in the last five years, many studies have been supporting this association between the unsaturated fats and diabetes.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:54.000
 And the other implications of Husai's work that coconut oil or saturated fats are protective and that sugar is protective,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:03.000
 are still showing up in the animal studies, but people aren't really thinking very much about them anymore.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:09.000
 I thought people with diabetes are supposed to watch their sugar intake.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:30.000
 Well, yeah, that was kind of a fad that comes and goes. The concept of complex carbohydrates, people advocated eating complex carbohydrates rather than sugars,

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:44.000
 and complex carbohydrates is just a silly way of saying starch, and starches are basically chains of glucose,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:57.000
 and glucose happens to be the single nutrient that most intensely disturbs insulin production.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:09.000
 And when you carefully look at food containing starch and food containing sucrose or lactose,

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:28.000
 the glycemic response is much greater from the starch than from the sugar. So someone trained dieticians to advocate the so-called complex carbohydrates.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:43.000
 Actually, they're the simplest carbohydrates in the sense that they're just a chain of glucose where sucrose is made up of one unit of glucose and one of fructose,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:08:04.000
 and lactose similarly is only half glucose. And this idea that for some reason starches were slower to disturb your blood sugar caught on widely,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:19.000
 but it's just part of the longer history in which diabetics have been put on high protein diets, high fat diets, low carbohydrate or high carbohydrate diets.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:36.000
 It just seems to go in periods of about 20 years each. The high fat diet, if it could be limited to the saturated fats such as coconut oil,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:09:00.000
 that would probably be a very good diet if it was also fairly high in protein. The trouble with a simply high protein diet is the protein stimulates your insulin secretion very powerfully the same way pure glucose or starch does.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:17.000
 So you don't want to overstimulate your pancreas for several reasons. It makes you store fat, for example, and it can overwork your pancreas.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:34.000
 For example, in experiments they would remove part of a dog's pancreas so that the remaining part had to work more intensely and various stresses would bring on chronic diabetes.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:10:01.000
 For example, one shot of cortisone would be enough to make such dogs diabetic and just a very intense overdose of starch or protein will cause such fluctuations in insulin and blood sugar that you get also a very intense cortisone reaction.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:18.000
 Yeah, the glucocorticoids are produced by the adrenals when your blood sugar falls sharply and any stress will bring that on.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:46.000
 And every night causes a sort of diabetes related action in which cortisone rises during the night, both adrenaline and cortisone, and diabetics have what they call the dawn phenomenon in which they're resistant to insulin after having spent the whole night in darkness

00:10:46.000 --> 00:11:14.000
 and at dawn their tissue doesn't respond to the insulin. Then during the daytime it does respond, and that's because the mitochondria in particular are damaged by darkness and stress and it creates a vicious circle in which the damaged mitochondria intensify the stress response.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:33.000
 That brings up the cortisol and growth hormone and adrenaline which mobilize fats from storage and block the ability to use glucose and so insulin has to rise but it's ineffective in those conditions.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:44.000
 Could we go back a little bit and maybe you could explain what exactly happens in diabetes and how the insulin, I don't really understand it myself.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:12:05.000
 Well, diabetes was originally defined, the name refers to excessive urination, and diabetics used to typically waste away because they couldn't assimilate food.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:23.000
 The diet of internal starvation and excessive urination was a basic feature and a lot of glucose being put into the urine was a basic feature.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:47.000
 And in this wasting condition the starving cells produce the stress reaction and that melts down the proteiny tissues of the body and so the protein is turned to sugar and they all have high blood sugar even if they don't eat.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:13:11.000
 And the old definition of diabetes has been modified to the point for several reasons that when someone says they're diabetic I just don't pay any attention to it because the word doesn't have any meaning anymore except basically high blood sugar.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:38.000
 And the death rate per 100,000 from diabetes increased when insulin became available and that was right in the official statistics all along.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:14:05.000
 And so people who investigated the issue by the 1930s knew that insulin wasn't lowering the death rate from diabetes and so people who studied it were very resistant to starting insulin treatment because they couldn't see any evidence that it was preventing death from diabetes.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:13.000
 That was something like doubling the death rate in the first 20 years after insulin came on the market.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:22.000
 That's an amazing statistic because growing up I thought that the development of insulin saved how it was utilized.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:50.000
 That's what the pharmaceutical industry always says that even though it often turns out differently like the cancer death rate has increased the more cancer therapy they apply is the higher the death rate is and you can't see any little change in the death rate from increasing mammography

00:14:50.000 --> 00:15:05.000
 or introducing new therapies or whatever. Every time they introduce something it's saving lives but when you look at the figures a few years later it increased the death rate usually.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:12.000
 So diabetes is a wasting disease?

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:37.000
 Haging itself is a wasting disease and stress produces wasting. But if they really wanted to diagnose classical diabetes they would measure the insulin in the blood.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:16:05.000
 When people have studied the role of insulin in regulating blood sugar they have found in one series of studies that the actual insulin molecule was only responsible for about 8% of the blood sugar disposition and other hormones

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:17.000
 and even just potassium in the food was a major factor in disposing of blood sugar. Potassium works like insulin.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:30.000
 And so one of the factors of a high starch diet is that starch tends to be compacted in foods as a storage molecule.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:53.000
 And it by forming a gigantic molecule can be stuffed somewhere in the cell and the rest of the cell with its normal concentration of potassium can be small in proportion to the high starch content.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:17:08.000
 So when you eat rice or any of the standard starchy foods you get very little potassium and magnesium along with your glucose equivalent.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:19.000
 And so it's the type of sugar which produces the most intense demands on your pancreas to produce insulin.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:40.000
 Where if you drank orange juice for example to get exactly the same amount of carbohydrate as in eating rice or bread your glucose for one thing is only half of the carbohydrate in the case of fruit juice.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:18:09.000
 Except for grape juice that's plain glucose but orange juice is only half glucose but this glucose is accompanied by lots of potassium and fair amounts of other minerals that help to dispose of the glucose harmlessly as a substitute for insulin or a complement to insulin.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:17.000
 What was your question?

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:21.000
 Well I was just sort of feeling our way through the diabetes issue here.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:40.000
 The insulin itself should be diagnostic of diabetes if diabetes is to be defined as an insulin deficiency or it's a reason for taking insulin.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:19:02.000
 But when that was investigated the insulin wasn't reliably diagnostic and so it's extremely rare for a doctor to actually measure insulin before diagnosing diabetes.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:13.000
 If a doctor prescribes thyroid hormone without measuring the amount of thyroid hormone in the body they lose their license.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
 It happens all the time.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:36.000
 But strangely because estrogen and insulin are such profitable big businesses no one ever bothers measuring your insulin for prescribing insulin or seldom they measure your actual estrogen before prescribing that.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:55.000
 When someone has pneumonia or some other viral infection and is in a stress condition turning their tissue to glucose to fight the infection they'll have extremely high blood sugar.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:14.000
 Very often these kids get put on insulin for the rest of their life with terrible side effects from taking too much insulin just because they had hyperglycemia without trying to find out why they had such high blood sugar.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:40.000
 And since the popularity of insulin treatment and the growing obesity of the population a new sort of official sub definition of diabetes has come into existence

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:50.000
 which it bypasses the problem that diabetes was being diagnosed without measuring insulin.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:21:17.000
 And so now they have the type of diabetes called insulin independent or it is basically the same as something called Syndrome X but non insulin dependent diabetes is really among middle aged people and older.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:37.000
 It's the main thing that's called diabetes and it's strictly a stress syndrome brought on by the hormone disruptions that commonly begin in the 30s and 40s.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:22:01.000
 And this form of diabetes is simply resistance of the tissue to insulin in the sense of disposing of glucose.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:09.000
 But the tissue is sensitive to insulin in the sense of turning on fat production.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:23.000
 And so one of the failures of diagnosis still is to look at what is really happening when you're resistant to insulin.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:40.000
 Is it real generalized resistance or is it simply that you turn everything to fat?

00:22:40.000 --> 00:23:03.000
 The stress reaction will produce a resistance of your liver to insulin but your fat cells become very sensitive to insulin and will produce fat while you maintain high blood sugar from the stress reaction.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:11.000
 So that's how being overweight is related to diabetes is that you just start producing fat cells?

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:25.000
 The stress reaction really is the explanation for the type of diabetes that isn't dependent on insulin.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:40.000
 In other words, insulin resistance is a stress reaction and everyone becomes relatively insulin resistant at dawn because of the stress of darkness.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:53.000
 The mitochondria deteriorate in the dark and so there aren't as many functional mitochondria to respond to dispose of sugar.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:24:04.000
 And that stress reaction and mitochondrial damage makes the body think that it's starving.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:10.000
 It's the same reaction that happened in classical diabetes leading to wasting away.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:15.000
 But it happens to everyone, every animal during the night.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:23.000
 The glucose isn't being metabolized because something is happening to the mitochondria.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:33.000
 And so the body senses a need for glucose so it turns on its cortisone to try to handle the stress.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:41.000
 And adrenaline always goes up when you're not getting enough glucose into your cells.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:25:00.000
 And these stress-related hormones, adrenaline, cortisone, growth hormone, prolactin, and acetylcholine, these four or five hormones, for example,

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:15.000
 will mobilize fat from storage and the fat then, especially if you have stored unsaturated fats into your fat cells,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:28.000
 the stress reaction brings the unsaturated fats out and your mitochondria try to metabolize these fats since they aren't able to get sugar.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:38.000
 And the unsaturated fats poison the mitochondria and intensify the insulin resistance.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:47.000
 But everyone has an increase of free fatty acids during the night showing that night is stressful to everyone.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:57.000
 And everyone's insulin resistance increases towards morning after they've been exposed to these free fatty acids all night.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:09.000
 And so the current knowledge of cell functioning and the stress reaction, this is confirming whose size work in the 40s

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:20.000
 showing that the saturated fats in coconut oil or even sugar, sucrose, would have a protective effect

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:31.000
 because it's turning out to be the unsaturated, polyunsaturated fatty acids which create insulin resistance.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:37.000
 There's a thing called the Randall cycle, which isn't really a cycle.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:48.000
 It just refers to the fact that your body stops metabolizing fats if it's able to metabolize sugar.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:54.000
 But if it's given an excess of fats, it can't metabolize sugar.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:07.000
 And so the Randall effect or Randall cycle is really a description of what happens in the so-called non-insulin dependent diabetes.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:17.000
 When you say sugar is protective, do you differentiate between sugars like fructose or white sugar?

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:25.000
 Well, when you study the effect of sucrose versus glucose, a given number of calories,

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:37.000
 the sucrose has a lower glycemic index, in other words, it is less disruptive to your pancreas.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
 It doesn't stimulate insulin so intensely.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:51.000
 And then when you break it down, it turns out not just that the fructose doesn't stimulate your pancreas very strongly,

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:58.000
 but when you combine glucose with fructose in the form of sucrose,

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:09.000
 the fructose actually impedes the glucose stimulation of the pancreas

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:24.000
 so that you get not just the 50% lower stimulation because the fructose isn't an active stimulant,

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:35.000
 but it's actually a retardant in stopping the glucose component from overstimulating your pancreas.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:42.000
 And the fact that sucrose so often comes with minerals is an extra factor,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:53.000
 but it's the fructose itself which offers protection against that glycemic reaction, which is so important in turning on fat production.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:59.000
 So I think you're saying the fructose is better because it doesn't overstimulate your pancreas.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:11.000
 Yeah, and so the best way to gain weight probably is to eat a high starch diet and a high unsaturated fat diet,

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:18.000
 exactly the things that have been recommended by dieticians for the last 30 years.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:25.000
 Yeah, and then they're wondering about why everybody's gaining weight, and they're just not getting enough exercise.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.000
 Turns out our kids are just plain lazy.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:36.000
 So I think they say weight is a risk factor for diabetes, don't they?

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:44.000
 They're blaming the weight for causing the disease.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:30:01.000
 Yeah, but the problem is that the diet blocks the ability to burn calories and shift the physiology to the storage of calories rather than the use of them.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:18.000
 Right. That makes sense. So if we're all running on cortisol and adrenaline at night, does that mean we shouldn't sleep at night?

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:29.000
 No. People have done studies having a tube in a vein so they could draw blood every 15 minutes,

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:38.000
 and doing these tests through the night with the lights on or off and people awake or asleep.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:49.000
 If they did the tests all night with the people awake, every 15 minutes there was a steep increase in the cortisol in the blood.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:58.000
 If the people were asleep, there was a less steep increase but still an increase.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:07.000
 And if they were doing the measurements with the lights on, there wasn't a noticeable increase.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:10.000
 As soon as the lights went off, the increase began.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:23.000
 And so if you have to be up at night, it's very important to have extremely bright lights around so that your body thinks that it's not really nighttime.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:40.000
 But ordinary room lights don't do the job. For example, sailors who were working the dark months in Antarctica had just ordinary room lights for 16 hours of the day.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:49.000
 And then when they went to sleep and turned off the lights, their physiology resembled that of very old people.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:32:00.000
 They went into an extreme alarm reaction immediately because their bodies weren't being properly conditioned by light.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:08.000
 The daytime light was inadequate so they were especially susceptible to the complete darkness for sleeping.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:22.000
 So the quality of daytime light is protective and the darkness is less harmful when you've been well illuminated during the day.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
 The charts charged up.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:40.000
 When you look at the mitochondria of rabbits around a 24-hour cycle, you see the mitochondria swelling up and breaking towards dawn, a progressive swelling and then exploding.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:52.000
 And then during the daytime they get progressively more normal until at sunset they're right back to fresh functioning mitochondria.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:33:05.000
 But in the winter, in the far north, these experiments were done in Leningrad where the winter nights are almost all day.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:18.000
 The mitochondria were in just disastrous condition and so the animals accumulated their aging decline during the winter months.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:29.000
 But if they survived then during the almost constant illumination of summer, they were highly rejuvenated so that they could get through another winter.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.000
 Yeah, it sounds like quite a roller coaster.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:38.000
 So that's why maybe people are, those light boxes where people are using those to fight depression.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
 Yeah, if they're bright enough.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:46.000
 But the light that penetrates happens to be red light.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:34:00.000
 The blue and ultraviolet, it does stimulate your brain, but it happens that both blue and ultraviolet cause stress and damage to your retina.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:07.000
 Whereas the yellow-green and red light is non-toxic to the retina.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:13.000
 And the longer wavelength of the light, the better it penetrates.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:23.000
 And the way when you see a flashlight shining through your hand or sunlight shining through a person's ears,

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:32.000
 the reason your hand or ear looks red is that it's the red light that passes deeply into your tissues.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:36.000
 So the red light at those heat lamps you can get at the hardware store, I believe?

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:47.000
 Yeah, that's red enough. Those clear-fronted so-called infrared lights, they're just designed to run on a high voltage.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:55.000
 So when you run them on 120 volts, the filament doesn't get as hot as in a regular light bulb.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:35:01.000
 That means that the light is biased away from blue towards yellow and red.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:05.000
 And so that's the penetrating beneficial light.

