 and he showed that each steroid has a curve like an upside-down V,

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:04.000
 that its peak is what people talk about as its main function.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:10.000
 But the shoulders of the curve overlap with other steroids,

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:21.000
 and he showed that the anabolic and androgenic functions were closely related.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:42.000
 The estrogenic functions were anti-anabolic and anti-androgenic. The progesterone category was anti-estrogenic and anti-androgenic,

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:53.000
 and also anti-glucocorticoids, or anti-cortisol. The glucocorticoids, or the cortisol type hormones,

00:37:53.000 --> 00:38:03.000
 were anti-anabolic and anti-androgenic to some degree,

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:23.000
 but primarily they are a catabolic type of hormone that, if you think of it as opposing the anabolic effects of the so-called androgens,

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:38.000
 that's probably the focus of what cortisol really is, and as having its anti-functions of the other hormones,

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:46.000
 some of the other hormones have pro-inflammatory functions, such as estrogen,

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:58.000
 and so the shoulders of this catabolic cortisol function happen to have a lot of other functions,

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:17.000
 so that people think of it as an anti-inflammatory hormone, but that's just one of its side effects.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:26.000
 This led to a lot of complications. People tend to name it in terms of a function rather than where it comes from.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:34.000
 Celie said that we should talk about hormones in terms of either their structure or where they come from,

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:46.000
 because they have so many functions, but turning protein to sugar is close to the essence of what the glucocorticoids do.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:59.000
 They're called that because of their sugar-raising function, and sugar then has the anti-inflammatory functions,

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:14.000
 and so the connection of sugar to cortisone to diabetes relates to its central function,

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:20.000
 which is to handle stress by feeding the organism.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:35.000
 It will turn primarily muscles to some extent skin and then liver into sugar when you're under stress,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:49.000
 so the protective effect of the anabolic hormones is essential so that you don't turn yourself totally to sugar every time you're under stress,

00:40:49.000 --> 00:41:02.000
 and for example, someone was using radioactive testosterone and thinking that they were going to produce images,

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:11.000
 radiological images, seeing where the concentration of radioactive testosterone was.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:24.000
 They thought it would be in the skeletal muscles, but it turned out that the heart was the most intensely concentrated focus of testosterone,

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:38.000
 and the heart happens to be a big concentrated muscle, but testosterone also protects the lungs and brain against the catabolic effects of cortisone.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:53.000
 So the balance of these hormones governs the shape of the body as you get old and have experienced a lot of stress.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:42:04.000
 You tend to get spindly legs and small muscles because you're constantly eating those, turning them to sugar,

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:12.000
 and in proportion to your cortisone balance, you'll tend to be thick around the torso with the accumulation of fat,

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:26.000
 or at an extreme you might get a moon face and a buffalo hump from fat deposits at the same time that your arms and legs become spindly.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:34.000
 But that's the picture of what cortisone dominance does over the whole body.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:47.000
 In the individual cell, it blocks the ability to use glucose, and that's how it kills some cells so selectively.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:55.000
 The thymus is probably the very first tissue to melt down under stress.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:04.000
 The white blood cells have their ability to get energy from sugar blocked by cortisone,

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:23.000
 and so they melt down and provide substance to make other brain tissue from. Your muscles melt down because they're being deprived of energy by the cortisone blockage of sugar use.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:35.000
 Luckily, the muscles have a balance of amino acids which turn off your thyroid so that you don't melt down so fast.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:53.000
 Especially if you're from prolonged stress or from aging, if your progesterone and testosterone levels have decreased beyond a certain protective level,

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:03.000
 your heart, lungs and brain are losing some of these anti-catabolic actions of progesterone and testosterone,

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:12.000
 and cortisone will now start eating away at these vital tissues rather than just your thymus and muscles.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:25.000
 The cortisone prevents your brain cells, if they aren't protected, from getting enough sugar to function and survive,

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:31.000
 and so they'll cause death of the brain cells and atrophy of the brain.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:45.000
 Simply, if you provide the brain cells with extra sugar in the presence of cortisone, they'll survive.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:45:11.000
 This blockage of the ability to use sugar is central to cortisone's function, and bringing the mitochondrion in is susceptible to several kinds of interference that prevent its ability to use glucose.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:24.000
 Nutritional deficiencies, for example, vitamin B1, a deficiency of that will prevent the use of glucose and create apparent diabetes.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:34.000
 Too much unsaturated fat will poison the mitochondrion and make it unable to use glucose.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:46.000
 Unsaturated fats and cortisone happen to have the same effect blocking mitochondrial respiration.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:51.000
 I think that's what Kim wants to know. What does the mitochondrion actually do?

00:45:51.000 --> 00:46:14.000
 The essential function, as far as the whole energy balance goes, of the mitochondrion is that it is where oxygen receives the electrons from glucose, primarily.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:39.000
 The most efficient thing is for glucose to be oxidized, giving up its electrons to oxygen, creating water and carbon dioxide as oxygen is also added to the carbon skeleton of the glucose.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:59.000
 Fats are metabolized in a slightly different pathway, also to oxygen, but there's a competition between fats and glucose, and the most efficient use of oxygen is when you're burning glucose.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:28.000
 If you're forced to burn fats, you lose efficiency, and if they're unsaturated fats, you not only lose efficiency, but you damage the structure of the mitochondrion because the electrons are not taken up quickly enough by oxygen and they escape to oxidize the mitochondrion.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:45.000
 If you cut off the oxygen supply or use for any reason, you tend to create damage and destruction of the mitochondria by these escaping electrons.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:48:08.000
 The thyroid function is to activate the enzymes which take up electrons, and so while thyroid intensifies oxidation, it's the proper oxidation that's pulling electrons through the mitochondrion and turning them harmlessly into water.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:26.000
 So if you interfere with thyroid, then you have the same effects that you get from cortisone or too much pre-fatty acid, especially pre-unsaturated fatty acids.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:34.000
 It's quite an amazing system, which I don't really understand completely, but it's quite a balancing act, isn't it?

00:48:34.000 --> 00:49:00.000
 When you take into account the effect of nighttime and daytime, the mitochondrion, it happens that red light, which penetrates into the cells, red light happens to repair the same enzyme that thyroid hormone is activating.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:15.000
 So a light deficiency acts on the enzymes exactly the same as the thyroid deficiency, and unsaturated fats poison the same enzyme system.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:42.000
 And so as far as mitochondrion is concerned, cortisone, unsaturated fat, hypoglycemic, hypothyroidism, and darkness, any of these things produces the same stress reaction in which oxidation is harmful rather than beneficial.

